Throughout blockaded Bolivia, the memory of a coast lost to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still present, as is the desire to sail the Pacific Ocean once again.
These hopes have not been so palpable in several decades, as Bolivia is awaiting a decision by the International Court of Justice, which will be rendered on 1 October, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the will, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course expects a positive outcome,” said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians will follow the decision of the International Court of Justice on the big screen across the country, hoping that the court in The Hague will rule in favor of the Bolivian request. Bolivia wants that, after decades of sporadic negotiations, Chile be required to negotiate the agreement on a sovereign passage to the ocean to Bolivia.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia (who faces a controversial fight for re-election next year), also has a lot to say about the decision to be made on Monday.
“We are so close to being able to return to the Pacific Ocean,” he said in late August.
But some analysts believe that there is little chance that the court will rule in favor of Chile, and that little would change, even if a positive decision were made.
The Netherlands-based UN body does not have the power to grant Chilean territory, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice renders its decision six months after the latest arguments shows that the case “was not complicated,” says Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And far from promoting the cause of Bolivia, the last four years may have even harmed it.
“The problem of access to the sea has been diverted by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
Morales’s bellicose rhetoric undermined all the goodwill that remained, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to exchange, but after that it will be very complicated to hold talks.
The last exchange of ambassadors between the two countries took place in 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodr<0xC3><0xAD>guez Veltzé, who represents Bolivia in The Hague, rejected the idea that the Court’s decision-making was abnormally fast.
Monday will bring Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance to “end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also disputed the fact that Morales - who remains to this day one of Latin America's most popular presidents - used the maritime problem as a political crutch.
