North Korea says that disarmament cannot be done unilaterally without trust.
On Saturday, the North Korean foreign minister told the United Nations that maintaining sanctions reinforced his distrust of the United States and that it would be impossible for his country to unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons in these circumstances.
At the World Organization's Annual General Assembly, Ri Yong Ho claimed that North Korea had taken "important goodwill measures" last year, such as ending nuclear and missile testing, dismantling the nuclear test site and its commitment not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
“However, we do not see any corresponding response from the United States,” he said.
In the absence of trust in the United States, we will fear for our national security, and in such circumstances it is excluded that we are the first to unilaterally disarm.”
While reiterating North Korea's well-known reproaches over Washington's opposition to a "step-by-step" approach to denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded if it gradually took action, his statement proved important in that it did not reject the idea of unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang had supposed.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, made on June 12 in Singapore at the very first summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader, when Kim pledged to work towards a “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea’s security.
North Korea seeks to officially end the Korean War (1950-1953), but the United States has declared that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also rejected calls to loosen tough international sanctions on North Korea.
The U.S. insists that North Korea first proceed with denuclearization and exacerbate pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve its goal coercively, even opposing “the declaration of end of war.”
“Those who think that these sanctions can make us ploy don’t know us.
The problem is that maintaining sanctions increases our distrust.”
Ri made no comment on the second summit between Kim and Trump highlighted before the United Nations by the US leader earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the party concerned with the issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a stalemate.”
Still, the tone of Ri's speech was radically different from last year's, when he told the United Nations General Assembly that it was inevitable to point North Korean missiles at North American territory after "evil" President Trump called Kim a "missile man" on a suicide mission.
Trump, who had threatened last year at the United Nations to "totally destroy" North Korea, has not quenched praise this year for the courage with which Kim has applied disarmament measures, but added that much remains to be done and that sanctions will not be lifted until North Korea disarms.
“It can take two years, three years or five months; it doesn’t matter,” Trump said.
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council last Thursday that “the application of Security Council sanctions must be firmly and systematically maintained until complete, definitive and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to stifle funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then announced that he would travel to Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
This year, Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times, but his last trip was somewhat disastrous.
In July, he left Pyongyang saying progress had been made, but in the hours that followed, North Korea denounced its “gangster methods.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site as well as a nuclear complex if the U.S. takes “equivalent measures.”
According to the South Korean president, Kim is demanding the security guarantees promised by Trump in Singapore, and efforts to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard: Students take rest classes
This year, Harvard University has put in place a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and fights the growing macho trend of studying by consuming caffeine all night long.
One professor noticed that most students at the world’s best university don’t know how to take care of them.
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him
In the end, a student came up and said, "Why are they telling me this only in the last year?"
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
For the first time this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their academic and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general manager of the university's health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The course time consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, books...) on which students click to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a routine before bedtime.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know this won’t change students’ behavior instantly.
However, in our opinion, they have the right to know this information – in the same way that you have the right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of the pride of “a blank night” still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students make sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Having enough sleep and good quality should be the “secret weapon” of students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said — even to avoid gaining weight, as lack of sleep puts the brain into starvation mode, making them starving all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian chemistry and physical biology student, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and pushed him to insist that it be offered to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all postgraduate students a similar curriculum before joining the reputable institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students provide an alarm for both bedtime and wake-up time, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and lead to sleep disturbances.
