The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
New research on an area in the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
The study by National Trust for Scotland researchers will follow common pipistrels and sopranos as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton in Inverewe Garden, Wester Ross.
Special registration devices will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable detectors.
A professional sound analysis will help determine the frequency of bat cries as well as the activities of different species.
A map and habitat report will be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important areas of habitat for bats and how these are used by each of these species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as grassland creation and how best to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by the construction and development work that affect the perches and lead to the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly papers and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by companion cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echolocation techniques to spot insects and obstacles on their flight path.
Responsible for protecting more than 270 historic buildings, 38 large gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, perch inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization has also established Scotland's first and only bat reserve at the Threave site in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, manager of the domain, says that the site is the ideal territory for them.
“Here in Threave, we have an ideal spot for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the good habitat.
But there is still a lot to learn about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what bats need to thrive.”
He stressed the importance of checking for bats before proceeding with the maintenance of the properties, because by unintentionally destroying a single maternity nest, it could result in the death of 400 females and young, or even the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, disturb, or destroy their perches.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and as far as many of our species are concerned, we don’t know what’s going on in their populations right now.”
