Red Tide Info Point: Decreased concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decline in red tide concentrations in some areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties - which raises concerns about declining concentrations.
The red tide covers about 209 km (130 miles) of coastline, from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee counties.
There are islets about 10 miles (16 km) off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer locations than last week.
Red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off Pinellas County have been reported last week, low to high concentrations off Hillsborough County, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations at the bottom of Sarasota County or offshore, medium concentrations in Charlotte County, and low concentrations at the bottom of Charlotte County or offshore, and low concentrations in Hillsborough County and offshore.
Cases of respiratory irritation persist in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
